<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE NATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The perception that air travel in the United States has become less safe is 
widespread, despite government statistics to the contrary, according to a 
Gallup Poll. Telephone interviews with 1,229 randomly selected adults Aug. 15 
to 18, a month after the crash of a United Airlines DC-10 in Sioux City, Iowa, 
found nearly two-thirds (63%) of Americans saying they have lost confidence in 
the safety and efficiency of airlines in recent years. Almost half (45%) of 
Americans who travel by commercial airliner say they at least sometimes feel 
frightened when they fly. However, nearly three-fourths (73%) feel that even 
with recent safety problems, air travel is still basically safe compared with 
other means of transportation. The survey has an error rate of plus or minus 4 
percentage points. 
</P>
