</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
POP MUSIC PREVIEW; 
</P>
<P>
JACKSON COMING TO IRVINE WITH A SURLY ATTITUDE, VERSATILE MUSIC 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE HOCHMAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
That Joe Jackson sure seems to be one arrogant chap, not to mention a surly 
cynic, contemptuous cuss and all-round critical dude. 
</P>
<P>
Oh yeah -- he's something of a snob as well. 
</P>
<P>
But those are probably the very qualities that over the last decade have 
allowed the New York-based Englishman to carve out an ambitious and distinctive 
body of uncompromising pop, much of which was on display Monday at the Wiltern 
Theatre in Los Angeles. Jackson will play Irvine Meadows Amphitheatre on Friday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
The nearly 2 1/2-hour set at the Wiltern covered both the wiry singer's 
eclectic career and -- in two six-song suites presenting his entire latest 
album, "Blaze of Glory" -- his lifetime. Jackson used the talents of a 
versatile 10-piece band to range from quasiclassical (his "Home Town" melody 
was set against an adaptation for horns and violin of Pachelbel's Canon in D) 
to biting rock ("I'm the Man") to jazzy jumpin' jive (a swinging encore 
medley). 
</P>
<P>
The horns in particular were used to provide sometimes Ellingtonian coloration 
to the songs (much the same way Steely Dan used to employ brass), adding new 
dimensions to old favorites. 
</P>
<P>
Within the set, especially the "Blaze of Glory" suites, Jackson ranged 
thematically from the New Frontier optimism of "Tomorrow's World" to the 
resigned frustration of "Evil Empire." 
</P>
<P>
Impressive indeed. While Jackson's no visionary (his music and especially his 
lyrics fall short of the kind of insightful abstractions that would qualify as 
poetic), the show left little doubt about his talent and ability to achieve his 
lofty artistic goals. 
</P>
<P>
But getting in the way of any real connection at each step was that dang 
attitude. Like Frank Zappa, another surly perfectionist, Jackson specializes in 
the put-down. On Monday, in one song after the other, Jackson aimed his snarly 
sneer at those he perceives as boobs: the ugly Americans of "Jet Set," the 
over-the-hill rocker -- performed by Jackson in a gravity-defying pompadour 
wig, silver lame coat and bulging prosthetic belly -- of "Nineteen Forever." 
</P>
<P>
Along the way he threw a brief snit at a sound mixer and sparred occasionally 
-- and not always good-naturedly -- with the audience. OK, the guy who asked 
for the songs to be sped up deserved the comeback, "Why don't you go see the 
Ramones?" And the nerd who got on stage and danced like a loon probably 
deserved more than the gentle kick in the derriere that Jackson gave him. 
</P>
<P>
And even when he complimented the crowd for its enthusiasm, he felt the need to 
note that past L.A. audiences had not been so good. The only people about whom 
he had anything unreservedly nice to say were the members of his band. 
</P>
<P>
If he has no sympathy or patience for anyone else, why should we have any for 
him? Admiration? Without question. Appreciation for his accomplishments? 
Indubitably. But not much honest, deep feeling. 
</P>
<P>
So when at the end of "Blaze of Glory" he sang, "All I want to do is give you 
the human touch," you had to wonder where it was. 
</P>
<P>
 Joe Jackson sings Friday at 8 p.m. at the Irvine Meadows Amphitheatre, 8800 
Irvine Center Drive, Irvine. Tickets: $21.50. Parking: $5. Information: (714) 
855-6111. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Joe Jackson specializes in the put-down. In one song after the other, 
Jackson aimed his snarly sneer at those he perceives as boobs. THOMAS KELSEY / 
Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
