<P>
DEPUTY NOT FAULTED IN HANDLING 911 CALL OF WOMAN SLAIN MINUTES LATER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sheriff Sherman Block today said a 911 dispatcher properly handled a call from 
a woman who was among four women slain 15 minutes later in an East Los Angeles 
birthday party rampage allegedly committed by her estranged husband. 
</P>
<P>
"The dispatcher did, in fact, function properly," Block told a news conference. 
"She did not violate any department policies or procedures." 
</P>
<P>
Maria Delia Navarro dialed 911 Sunday night after being warned that her husband 
was going to shoot up her 27th birthday party. The dispatcher told her to call 
back if the man arrived. About 15 minutes later, Raymond Navarro Jr. allegedly 
burst into the converted garage that his estranged wife was renting and began 
firing a handgun. 
</P>
<P>
Block said the deputy who took the call is a Latina sensitive to the Eastside 
community in which she worked. "We don't find any fault with the way she 
proceeded," he said. 
